Cars4U Project¶

Key analysis objectives of the Project¶

  1. Explore and visualize the dataset.
  2. Build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars.
  3. Generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business

Data Context¶

The objective of the analysis is to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. Following details are available to come up with the model which can help achieve the business objectives.

  1. S.No. : Serial Number
  2. Name : Name of the car which includes Brand name and Model name
  3. Location : The location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase Cities
  4. Year : Manufacturing year of the car
  5. Kilometers_driven : The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in KM.
  6. Fuel_Type : The type of fuel used by the car. (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  7. Transmission : The type of transmission used by the car. (Automatic / Manual)
  8. Owner : Type of ownership
  9. Mileage : The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  10. Engine : The displacement volume of the engine in CC.
  11. Power : The maximum power of the engine in bhp.
  12. Seats : The number of seats in the car.
  13. New_Price : The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs.(1 Lakh = 100, 000)
  14. Price : The price of the used car in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh = 100, 000)

Data Analysis:¶

Car and its sales profile based on the data set:

  1. S.No Range is from 0 to 7252 and there are no missing values
  2. Total unique cars names are 2041 and there are no missing values
  3. Total unique locations of sales are 11 and no value is missing
  4. Car sales data available in dataset are from year 1996 to 2019.There are no missing values
  5. Kilometer driven is available for all rows
  6. There 5 unique fuel type and there are no null values. More than 50% of vehicles listed are Diesel type
  7. There are two unique transmission type and values for all the rows are available. There are far more manual transmission vehicles.
  8. There are 4 unique Owner type and highest being the first. No missing values.
  9. Mileage , Engine type, Power, seats, New price and Price columns have many missing values
  10. There is a correlation between missing values of Engine and Power.
  11. Some cars have 0 number of seats which appears inconsistent, unless we also have driver and passenger less self driving cars in the list. (As the data is from India and such cars are not allowed in open market as per regulation hence this inconsistency need to be addressed)
  12. These are no columns which need to be dropped at this stage of analysis. All the columns in data frame appears useful for further analysis.
  13. For getting additional details further processing of data need to carried out.

def missingvaluecheck(dat): #function to find missing values within the dataset
    calc_total = dat.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False) #Checking for total null values
    calc_percent = (dat.isnull().sum()/dat.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False) #checking percentage
    data_missing = pd.concat([calc_total, calc_percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', '% of Missing Val']) #to display missing data count and percentage
    return data_missing # return the dataframe

Change Cr to Lakh and removed the string part of the variables¶

In [12]:
def cr_to_lakh(var):
    if isinstance(var, str):  # checking if the value is string or not
        if "Cr" in var:  # checking for the presence of Cr
            spl = var.split(" ")  # splitting the value by space
            new_val = (
                float(spl[0].replace("Cr", "")) * 100
            )  # taking numeric part and converting to lakh
            return new_val
        else:
            return float(var.replace("Lakh", ""))  # taking numeric part of Lakh
    else:
        return np.nan  # will return NaN if value is not string

#### function to remove the suffixes from the columns
#Alert: This function will remove any suffix without considering the values of suffix
def remove_given_prefix_cols(str_val): 
    if isinstance (str_val,str): #check id the value is string type
        spl_val=str_val.split(" ") #split the string value based on single space (Not to be used without checking if numeric data have embedded space)
        if spl_val[0] == "null":   #to handle null string saved in the Power column
            return float(0)
        else:
            return float(spl_val[0])
    else:
        return np.nan
    
car4udf['Mileage'] = car4udf['Mileage'].apply(remove_given_prefix_cols) #removing prefix
car4udf['Engine'] = car4udf['Engine'].apply(remove_given_prefix_cols) #removing prefix
car4udf['Power'] = car4udf['Power'].apply(remove_given_prefix_cols) #removing prefix

In [64]:
# Adjusted R^2
def adj_r2(ind_vars, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = ind_vars.shape[0]
    k = ind_vars.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# Model performance check
def model_perf(model, inp, out):

    y_pred = model.predict(inp)
    y_act = out.values

    return pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_act, y_pred)),
            "MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_act, y_pred),
            "R^2": r2_score(y_act, y_pred),
            "Adjusted R^2": adj_r2(inp, y_act, y_pred),
        },
        index=[0],
    )
